{{ comp callout { type: "note", title: "Alpha — API subject to change" } }}
NetScript is a backend framework and workspace generator, not a hosted service — you run it on
Deno and own all the generated code. We are on the path to beta, targeting late 2026, and the API
is still moving. Every <code>@netscript/*</code> package shares one aligned version
(<code>0.0.1-alpha.0</code>) and releases move in lockstep, so pin your versions. A few scaffolded
<code>jsr:…@^1.0.0</code> specifiers are forward-looking rather than installable today.
{{ /comp }}

{{ comp.tabbedCode({ tabs: [
  { label: "Define a service", lang: "ts", code: "// One preset wires CORS, request logging, OpenAPI JSON, Scalar docs,\n// RPC (served at /api/rpc/*), service info, and health endpoints —\n// instead of ~40 lines of Hono setup.\nimport { defineService } from '@netscript/service';\nimport { router } from './router.ts';\n\nconst service = await defineService(router, {\n  name: 'users',\n  port: 3000,\n});\n\nawait service.stop();" },
  { label: "Install & scaffold", lang: "sh", code: "# Install the netscript command from JSR\ndeno install --global --allow-all --name netscript jsr:@netscript/cli/bin/netscript.ts\n\n# Scaffold a complete, type-checked workspace\nnetscript init my-app\n\n# Prefer to keep .NET Aspire out of the loop? Opt out:\nnetscript init my-app --no-aspire" },
  { label: "Bring it up", lang: "sh", code: "# Aspire is step 2: it brings up Postgres and Garnet first\ncd my-app/aspire && aspire run\n\n# Then, in the workspace root, initialize the database\nnetscript db init\n\n# Open the Aspire dashboard at http://localhost:18888 to see\n# every resource, service, trace, and log in one place." }
] }) }}

<h2>Build real systems, not just CRUD</h2>

{{ comp.featureGrid({ items: [
  { title: "Contract-first, type-safe end to end", body: "oRPC contracts flow from service to client to UI with no codegen drift. The type checker is your integration test. Services are served at /api/rpc/*.", href: "/capabilities/services/" },
  { title: "Orchestrated with Aspire", body: "We borrow .NET Aspire for multi-resource local dev, deploy, and a real dashboard — unusual in TypeScript. One workspace wires it all; opt out with --no-aspire.", href: "/explanation/aspire/" },
  { title: "Durability model by design", body: "Sagas, triggers, and jobs are explicit state machines with correlation, persistence (KV or Prisma), compensation, and supervised crash boundaries — authored in plain TypeScript builders.", href: "/capabilities/durable-sagas/" },
  { title: "Authentication, pluggable backend", body: "An auth-api service on :8094 with five endpoints. The core defines one port; swap between kv-oauth (interactive), WorkOS, or better-auth without touching your service code.", href: "/capabilities/auth/" },
  { title: "Observable by default", body: "OpenTelemetry tracing and structured logs are wired into jobs, queues, RPC, schedulers, and subprocess workers from line one — not bolted on later.", href: "/explanation/observability/" },
  { title: "Composable plugins", body: "Add workers, sagas, triggers, auth, and streams in any combination. The host never changes.", href: "/capabilities/background-jobs/" }
] }) }}

<h2>Who it is for</h2>

{{ comp.featureGrid({ items: [
  { title: "Full-stack TypeScript engineers", body: "Stay in TypeScript from the database to the UI, with contracts that catch integration breaks before they ship." },
  { title: "Platform engineers", body: "Standardize internal services on one coherent Deno baseline — multi-resource wiring, a real dashboard, pluggable auth, and tracing already in place." },
  { title: "Plugin authors", body: "Extend the framework by registering workers, sagas, triggers, auth backends, and streams. No host edits, no forks." }
] }) }}

